column2:
['To the valley and the river small,
The cattle, the grass, the bare ash trees,
The chickens from the farmsteads, all
Elm-hidden, and the tributaries', 'Chariots rumbling; horses neighing;
Soldiers shouting martial cries;
Drums are sounding; trumpets braying;
Seas of glittering spears arise.']

['The lonely bridge cuts dark across the marsh
Whose long pools glow with the light
Of a flaming summer sunset.
At this end limp bushes overhang,
Palely reflected in the amber-colored water.', 'I see the tracks of the railroads of the earth;
I see them welding State to State, city to city, through North America;
I see them in Great Britain, I see them in Europe;
I see them in Asia and in Africa.']

column4:
I see the tracks of the railroads of the earth;
I see them welding State to State, city to city, through North America;
I see them in Great Britain, I see them in Europe;
I see them in Asia and in Africa.

Explanation: The first passage describes a specific scene with a bridge and sunset, while the second passage discusses railroads connecting various parts of the world, which aligns more with the context of J. R. Dos Passos' "The Bridge" and Walt Whitman's "Salut au Monde!" which often explore themes of connectivity and global perspectives.
